===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|mous}}, from {{inh|en|ang|mūs}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*mūs}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*mūs}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*muh₂s}}.
{{rel-top|cognates}}
Germanic cognates include {{cog|ofs|mūs}}, {{cog|osx|mūs}} ({{cog|nds-de|Muus}}), {{cog|nl|muis}}, {{cog|goh|mūs}} ({{cog|de|Maus}}), {{cog|non|mús}} ({{cog|sv|mus}}, {{cog|da|mus}}, {{cog|no|mus}}, {{cog|is|mús}}, {{cog|fo|mús}}).

Indo-European cognates include {{cog|grc|μῦς}}, {{cog|la|mūs}}, {{cog|es|mur}}, {{cog|hy|մուկ|sc=Armn}}, {{cog|cu|мꙑшь|sc=Cyrs}} ({{cog|ru|мышь}}), {{cog|sq|mi}}, {{cog|fa|sc=fa-Arab|موش|tr=muš}},{{cog|kmr|mişk}},{{cog|sa|मूष्}}.
{{rel-bottom}}

The computing sense was {{coin|en|nocap=1|nobycat=1|Bill English|w=Bill English (computer engineer)|nat=American|occ=engineer|in=1965}} and first used publicly in a publication titled "Computer-Aided Display Control".

